<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,151,1165]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1068,1093]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet is a contraction of the 
<collectingCountry box="[878,929,1068,1093]" name="Thailand" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Thai</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[943,1158,1068,1093]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">nam tok hin poon</emphasis>
meaning tufa (literally ‘limestone waterfall’) in reference to the species’ clear preference for tufa habitats. It is used as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/289951/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" targetBox="[159,1421,1225,1765]" targetPageId="35">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1799,1853]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,332,1799,1822]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">FIGURES 53–54</emphasis>
. Male terminalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[539,856,1800,1822]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="namtokhinpoon" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[539,856,1800,1822]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicName box="[539,692,1800,1822]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hemerodromia</taxonomicName>
namtokhinpoon
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[861,973,1800,1821]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[861,942,1800,1821]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
53
</emphasis>
, lateral view of terminalia; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1254,1279,1800,1821]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">54</emphasis>
, dorsal view of cerci. Abbreviations: cer = cerci, epa = epandrium, hyp = hypandrium.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1892,2025]" lastBlockId="36.[151,1437,151,290]" lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1892,1917]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species may be distinguished from other predominantly yellow species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1267,1436,1892,1917]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1267,1436,1892,1917]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Hemerodromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[301,401,1928,1953]" name="Thailand" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Thailand</collectingCountry>
by its complex crenate cercus and elongate epandrium which bears a very strong apical bristle. All but one of the 
<specimenCount box="[445,598,1964,1989]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="generic">
<number box="[445,473,1965,1989]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="39.0">39</number>
specimens
</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[637,846,1964,1989]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="namtokhinpoon" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[637,846,1964,1989]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">H. namtokhinpoon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[854,944,1964,1989]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[854,944,1964,1989]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
examined were taken in close proximity to basic and mineral rich tufa streams (
<figureCitation box="[567,651,2000,2025]" captionStart="FIGURES 82 – 90" captionStartId="48.[151,264,1913,1936]" captionTargetBox="[292,1274,205,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[277,1305,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 82 – 90. Distribution of Hemerodromia spp. in Thailand at a resolution of 0.25 ° and symbols sized to 0.5 ° of latitude and longitude. 82, H. demissa sp. nov.; 83, H. epsilutea sp. nov.; 84, H. etalutea sp. nov.; 85, H. flaviventris Yang &amp; Yang; 86, H. furcata Grootaert, Yang &amp; Saigusa; 87; H. fusca Yang &amp; Yang; 88, H. gammalutea sp. nov.; 89, H. isochita sp. nov.; 90, H. namtokhinpoon sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/289960/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<number box="[622,651,2001,2025]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="90.0">90</number>
</figureCitation>
) in Loei Province, northeast 
<collectingCountry box="[984,1087,2000,2025]" name="Thailand" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Thailand</collectingCountry>
. (Suan Hom, conductivity 
<number box="[1394,1436,2001,2025]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="414.0">414</number>
µS/cm 
<number box="[223,231,151,165]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
, pH 
<number box="[295,347,155,179]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="8.08">8.08</number>
; Suan Sawan conductivity 
<number box="[668,710,155,179]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="418.0">418</number>
µS/cm 
<number box="[794,802,151,165]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
, pH 
<number box="[865,919,155,179]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="7.84">7.84</number>
). The two specimens from Tat Mueng were captured from a basic (pH 
<number box="[453,505,194,218]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="7.21">7.21</number>
), but less mineralised stream (conductivity 
<number box="[997,1025,194,217]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="77.0">77</number>
µS/cm 
<number box="[1105,1113,190,204]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="2.0">2</number>
), lacking in tufa formations. The tufa streams inhabited by 
<taxonomicName box="[498,708,229,254]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Hemerodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="namtokhinpoon" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[498,708,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">H. namtokhinpoon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[717,808,229,254]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[717,808,229,254]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
flow through predominantly dry forest biotopes at low elevation (
<quantity box="[268,401,265,290]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.935" metricValueMax="6.27" metricValueMin="5.6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" unit="m" value="593.5" valueMax="627.0" valueMin="560.0">560–627 m</quantity>
). Adults have been captured in late November during the cool dry season.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
